  <mads:note type="history">Smith's Dictionary, Volume 2, pg. 546: "Jacobus Diaconus, the Deacon,
  or of Edessa, It is doubtful of what church Jacobus was deacon. Baronius contends for Heliopolis in Coele-Syria, but Pagi and
  Assemani think he belonged rather to Edessa. He appears to have lived about the middle of the 5th century, and is known only
  as the author of Vita S. Pelagiae Meretricis Antiochiae, " The Life of Saint Pelagia, the Harlot of Antioch," written
  in Greek, of which a Latin version, by one Eustachius, is given by Surius, in his De Probatis Sanctorum Vitis..."</mads:note>
